snippet.textDisplay:
The problem with Khabib is twofold. First, as a wrestler, he gets an inherent advantage based on the rule set which governs the sport. He is allowed to shoot for take downs(exposing the back, neck, spine) without any repercussions short of a stuff. This is not Khabib's fault, but it is an advantage for the guy who relies on ground and pound almost completely.

Second, He has hella cardio!

The way to beat him is to focus on the Jab, knowing he will look to shoot under it for take downs. If this is anticipated correctly, you can shift weight
(pushing out legs) and ride Khabib's back down(Similar to the way Chuck Liddel use to stuff take down attempts early in his career.) The key is to be patient and make Khabib act. If you keep the fight on those terms, it will nullify Khabib's greatest weapons and allow you to chip away with the jab.

It won't be a pretty fight, but it will be effective because we all know Khabib is the epitome of a "One trick pony." Ferguson will lose to Khabib, because he will look to go toe to toe, which Khabib will ignore and go straight for the only thing he knows(Ground and Pound.) Once he gets Ferguson on his back it'll be a slow grind to the TKO as it always is With Khabib.

snippet.textDisplay: I know it sounds crazy, but i see khabib having the best stand up in mma too. He comes forward with pressure and doesnt let you strike with him. If you stop backing up and punch or kick hes coming for a takedown, if you dont set to throw anything then he continues moving forward and throws big punches. He basically takes away any good options you have while constantly waging an attrition battle on you. Combined all this with his mental toughness & i think he has the overall best stand up in the sport. And im not gonna check, but id imagine that out of all top level guys he probably has the biggest discrepancy in standing  strikes landed to strikes recieved. Anyways just a thought, tell me what u guys think.✌😩✌

snippet.textDisplay: I'm reminded of when Diego Sanchez challenged BJ Penn for the lightweight title, and I thought Diego had the tools to stand and outstrike Penn.  To my and I'm sure everyone else's surprise, Diego spend the majority of the fight pushing Penn against the fence, clutching to the same fruitless single leg attempt until Penn got free long enough to split his head open with that kick.  After watching this video, I can't help but think this was Diego's coaches focusing more on what they <del>thought</del> was Penn's weakness and less on the skillset that made Diego the beast he was at the time.
snippet.textOriginal: I'm reminded of when Diego Sanchez challenged BJ Penn for the lightweight title, and I thought Diego had the tools to stand and outstrike Penn.  To my and I'm sure everyone else's surprise, Diego spend the majority of the fight pushing Penn against the fence, clutching to the same fruitless single leg attempt until Penn got free long enough to split his head open with that kick.  After watching this video, I can't help but think this was Diego's coaches focusing more on what they -thought- was Penn's weakness and less on the skillset that made Diego the beast he was at the time.

snippet.textDisplay: Chael, if you want to beat khabib, I think not only staying in the center away from the cage, but putting khabib's back against the cage. He uses his posturing and his legs to secure every single take down, and by that I mean using his legs to either pull there's away or by locking their legs with his. Any time he shoots in the open, he pretty much fails because he is using his legs to explode off rather than wrapping around his opponent.  Put his back against the cage and you can pretty much eliminate the takedown, and then just keep the pressure on him. What so you think?

snippet.textDisplay: Well I think something interesting going into this fight is Tony will make Khabib bleed. And that’s something I don’t think we have ever seen Khabib deal with. To be honest I’m excited to see how Khabib deals with this. Khabib has been vsing Guys he could prepare for. This is why in the first round against Conor he wasn’t risking that left hand until he gassed him a little and he went straight for the takedown. The issue I see for Khabib is how do you prepare for a guy like Tony. Someone who is almost unpredictable in his movements and skills. Ok so he has his chin high when backing up. Khabib might catch him with a flying knee but I don’t think Khabib will be in striking range. Tony is also not scared to 1 go to the ground and 2 be on his back. These are all things Khabib has taken advantage of making his opponents uncomfortable. Barboza and Dustin come to mind especially. That’s not going to be the case for Tony. No matter how you slice it this will be Khabib’s hardest fight ever.
